# 📍 Day 2 — EBS, EFS & Load Balancers

## 🎯 Objective

Understand AWS storage solutions and how traffic is distributed in scalable systems.

---

## 💾 EBS (Elastic Block Store)

### 📌 Key Points

* Block storage attached to EC2
* Persistent (data survives reboot)
* Types: SSD (fast), HDD (cheap)

### 📌 Use Cases

* Databases
* Operating systems
* Applications requiring low latency

---

## 📂 EFS (Elastic File System)

### 📌 Key Points

* Managed file storage (like shared drive)
* Can be accessed by multiple EC2 instances
* Automatically scales

### 📌 Use Cases

* Shared content (web servers)
* Distributed applications

---

## ⚖️ EBS vs EFS

| Feature     | EBS           | EFS            |
| ----------- | ------------- | -------------- |
| Type        | Block storage | File storage   |
| Usage       | Single EC2    | Multiple EC2   |
| Scalability | Manual        | Automatic      |
| Use Case    | Databases     | Shared systems |

---

## 🌐 Load Balancers

### 📌 Purpose

* Distribute traffic across multiple EC2 instances
* Improve availability and fault tolerance

### 📌 Types (Overview)

* **ALB (Application Load Balancer)** → HTTP/HTTPS traffic
* **NLB (Network Load Balancer)** → TCP/UDP, high performance

---

## 💡 Key Learnings

* EBS = performance-focused storage
* EFS = scalable shared storage
* Load balancing is critical for high availability

---

## 🚧 Challenges Faced

* Differentiating EBS vs EFS use cases
* Understanding load balancer types

